o (Catholic) Purgatory? and is there cause-and-effect here? How can Lancelot Gobbo be correct (and he is) when he claims Black Monday (the day after Easter) and Ash Wednesday (the 41st day before Easter) once fell on the same day? And what is a ‘dram of eale’? This engaging and lucid book solves these tantalizing riddles and many others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRiddles in literature. 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aCrucifixion.  aGabriel Harvey.  aHamlet.  aJames I.  aJulius Caesar.  aMacbeth.  aOthello.  aRomeo and Juliet.  aShakespeare's riddles.  acalendrical anomalies.  acognoscenti.  areligious dogma.1 aSohmer, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613512440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526135124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526135124/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles